i\/1938_in_literature\" title=\"1938 in literature\">1938<\/a>, she was awarded the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Literature\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Literature\">Nobel Prize in Literature<\/a> \"for her rich and truly epic descriptions of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Rural_society_in_China\" title=\"Rural society in China\">peasant life in China<\/a> and for her <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Biographical\" title=\"Biographical\" class=\"mw-redirect\">biographical<\/a> masterpieces\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Pearl_S._Buck#cite_note-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> She was the first American woman to win the Nobel Prize for Literature.<\/p><p>After returning to the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States\" title=\"United States\">United States<\/a> in 1935, she continued writing prolifically and became a prominent advocate of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Rights_of_women\" title=\"Rights of women\" class=\"mw-redirect\">rights of women<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Minority_rights\" title=\"Minority rights\">minority<\/a> groups, and wrote widely on <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Culture_of_Asia\" title=\"Culture of Asia\">Asian cultures<\/a>, becoming particularly well known for her efforts on behalf of Asian and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Interracial_adoption\" title=\"Interracial adoption\">mixed-race adoption<\/a>.<\/p>","name":"Pearl S. Buck","place_of_birth":"Hillsboro ,  West Virginia , United States","place_of_death":"Danby ,  Vermont , United States","text":"Pearl S. Buck , Literature, 1938","year":1938.0}